title: Which Led Zeppelin albums do you view as subpar? - Quora

response.answer_text: Well that’s a tough one . but i’ll try to answer . a short answer would be everything after physical graffiti which came in 1975 . but if we take a closer look even some of these weaker led zeppelin albums packed so much punch most of the bands couldn’t come close to it . from presence(1976) we got:- for your life - amazing song with powerful guitar solo and drums , Achilles last stand :- in my opinion one of the greatest guitar performances of all time . then there’s tea for , nobody’s fault but mine , then from ITTOD we got fool in the rain which again ranks as of the best jimmy page solos of all time and a few other decent tracks . so even though band was going through hard times during late 70s like jimmy and john’s addiction , jpj’s famiy and robert plant;s accident still they were performing live and putting out music . as jimmy said after ITTOD his intention was to go to early days of led zeppelin and kinda make a classic album . as we know it that album was never made . despite of these ups and downs during their career many people including me consider led zeppelin as of the the greatest artists of all time (and probably the most talented :) )

None. Zero. I have various levels of greatness for them… Level 1: Physical Graffiti Presence III The Song Remains the Same The first album Level 2: II How the West Was Won BBC Sessions Level 3: The fourth album Houses of the Holy Coda In Through the Our Door I love every Zep album. Even my least favorites aren't sub par… Incidentally, I don't consider Celebration Day as a Zeppelin album, but an awesome tribute, since Little Bonzo isn't his father, but he turns in an incredible performance…

Same with Pink Floyd and Queen, I think a lot of their later stuff gets way too much hate, except for Coda. That album is just generally not all that good. It has basically no thought put into it. All of the songs are just leftovers from previous recording sessions. It only exists to fulfill a contract the band had with their record label. They didn't wanna record new stuff after Bonham was gone so Jimmy Page gathered a bunch of these old songs.

I have never been a fan of Presence (1976) although I do like two tracks. Those being ‘Achilles Last Stand” and “Nobody’s Fault But Mine”. I have never owned “In Through the Out Door” (1979) or “Coda” (1982) and find both subpar compared to their first six albums. There are fine moments on these albums but nothing like what used to be.
I don’t know if it’s sub-par per se, but my least favorite Led Zeppelin album is Presence. Other than “Achilles Last Stand” and “Nobody’s Fault But Mine,” the other tracks don’t stand out for me.

I’d have to say Coda is the worst, followed by Presence. I grew up listening to hits so I want to hear some on an album. Nobody’s Fault But Mine is about the only song on both albums that is worth hearing.
